  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions dates back several decades, with significant developments occurring primarily in the latter half of the 20th century. Here's an overview of key milestones:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in response to organized crime and drug trafficking\n- United States passed the Bank Secrecy Act in 1970, requiring financial institutions to report certain transactions\n\n2. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs introduced international money laundering controls\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989 to develop global AML standards\n\n3. Major Legislative Landmarks:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- U.S. Patriot Act of 2001 significantly expanded AML regulations after 9/11\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives progressively strengthened regulatory frameworks\n\n4. Modern Era:\n- Increased focus on digital currency and cryptocurrency regulations\n- Expanding international cooperation in tracking and preventing financial crimes\n- Growing emphasis on beneficial ownership transparency\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
